<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11595&amp;p=133333#p133333</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11595&amp;p=133333#p133333"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Nestopia RGB bug?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11595&amp;p=133333#p133333"><![CDATA[
Polite administrative request:<br /><br />Please stop turning this board into an emulator bug reporting forum.  For Nestopia there is an existing ticketing system on github for this exact thing.  For other emulators, most of the authors provide an Email address, or a forum of their own.  This is not a place to just dump bug reports for individual emulators, as long as those emulators have reachable authors or existing support outlets.<br /><br />I say this with full acknowledgement that it can be useful for many people to provide insights into something, and say &quot;oh hey MAYBE this is a more widespread emulation bug&quot;, but that isn't how this thread (or <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=3&amp;t=11594" class="postlink">the other recent thread</a>) is being presented.  It's more of &quot;look, something doesn't work, I like taking screenshots and pasting them and then saying bug, clicking Submit, and see what happens&quot;.<br /><br />And when it comes to romhacks, all bets are off.  Really.  Even I'm responsible for problems with romhacks I've worked on/coded!<br /><br />TL;DR -- If there's an issue with an emulator you're using, report the bug to the emulator author(s) first, not this board.  If the bug is repeatable on multiple emulators (especially those which are known to have good PPU and CPU implementations), and seems to imply something like a mapper quirk, sure, discuss it here and provide full reproduction details.  One-liners do not help anyone.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3">koitsu</a> — Sat Aug 30, 2014 11:14 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
